[[File:ПГУ_им._Шолом-Алейхема.jpg|thumb|Sholem Aleichem Amur State University]] '''Sholem Aleichem Amur State University''' ({{lang-ru|Приамурский государственный университет имени Шолом-Алейхема}}), formerly '''Birobidzhan State Pedagogical Institute''', is a [[university]] in [[Russia]]. This is the only university based in the [[Jewish Autonomous Oblast]]. It is named after Jewish-Russian author [[Sholem Aleichem]].
==Overview== The university works in cooperation with the local Jewish community of [[Birobidzhan]] and the [[Birobidzhan Synagogue]]. It is unique in the [[Russian Far East]]. The basis of the training courses is study of the [[Hebrew language]], history and classic [[Jewish]] texts.<ref>{{cite web|author=Информационно-аналитическое управление правительства ЕАО |url=http://www.eao.ru/eng/?p=365 |title=Еврейская автономная область - официальный портал |publisher=Eao.ru |date= |accessdate=2016-05-03}}</ref>
In recent years, the [[Jewish Autonomous Oblast]] has grown interest in its [[Jewish]] roots. Students study Hebrew and [[Yiddish]] at the Jewish school and Birobidzhan Jewish National University. In 1989, the Jewish Center founded a [[Sunday school]], where children can study Yiddish, learn [[Jewish]] [[folk dance|folk]] [[dance]], and [[history of Israel]]. The [[Israeli government]] helps fund this program.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vn.vladnews.ru/Arch/2000/ISS207/focus.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=February 18, 2009 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090204084032/http://vn.vladnews.ru/Arch/2000/ISS207/focus.html |archivedate=February 4, 2009 }}</ref>
In 2007, the first Birobidzhan International Summer Program for Yiddish Language and Culture was launched by Boris Kotlerman, a Yiddish studies professor at [[Bar-Ilan University]].<ref name="autogeneratedil">{{cite web|url=http://www.2all.co.il/web/Sites/yiddishproject/ |title=Yiddish Summer School in Birobidzhan, Home |publisher=2all.co.il |date= |accessdate=2016-05-03}}</ref> Yiddish is still the region’s second [[official language]] after [[Russian language|Russian]], although it is spoken only by a handful of 4,000 remaining Jews.<ref>{{cite web|last=Liphshiz |first=Cnaan |url=http://www.jta.org/cgi-bin/iowa/account/new/index |title=Index for a million documents on Polish Jewry to go online &#124; Jewish Telegraphic Agency |publisher=Jta.org |date=2013-02-20 |accessdate=2016-05-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jta.org/cgi-bin/iowa/news/article/20070814Yiddishprogram.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2007-09-01 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20070621171021/http://www.jta.org/cgi-bin/iowa/news/article/20070814Yiddishprogram.html |archivedate=2007-06-21 |df= }}</ref> This program includes a workshop on the village of [[Valdgeym]] and its Yiddish [[Cultural heritage|heritage]].<ref name="autogeneratedil"/>
